<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What are meta tags and why do they matter for SEO?", answer: "Meta tags are HTML elements in the <head> section that provide metadata about a web page. The title tag and meta description are the most important for SEO because search engines display them in search results. A well-crafted title and description improve click-through rates. Other meta tags like robots control crawling behavior, while viewport ensures mobile responsiveness." },
  { question: "What is the ideal length for a meta title?", answer: "Google typically displays the first 50-60 characters of a title tag. Titles over 60 characters may be truncated in search results with an ellipsis. Best practice is to keep titles under 60 characters while including your primary keyword near the beginning. Every page should have a unique title that accurately describes the content." },
  { question: "What is the ideal length for a meta description?", answer: "Meta descriptions should be between 120-160 characters. Google may display up to 155-160 characters on desktop and fewer on mobile. While meta descriptions do not directly affect rankings, they heavily influence click-through rates. Include a clear value proposition and a call to action. If no meta description is set, Google will auto-generate one from the page content." },
  { question: "What are Open Graph tags?", answer: "Open Graph (OG) tags control how your page appears when shared on social media platforms like Facebook, LinkedIn, and others. The key tags are og:title (the sharing title), og:description (sharing description), og:image (preview image), og:url (canonical URL), and og:type (content type). Without OG tags, social platforms guess what to display, often producing poor results." },
  { question: "What are Twitter Card tags?", answer: "Twitter Card tags control how your page appears when shared on Twitter/X. The twitter:card tag defines the card type: 'summary' shows a small image with text, 'summary_large_image' shows a large featured image. Twitter also reads Open Graph tags as fallbacks, so if you have OG tags set, Twitter cards will work even without Twitter-specific tags." }
]) %>

